ce:section.ce:para:
Sugarcane is the most sugar-rich crop, with up to 12 % sucrose, glucose and fructose. To optimize the utilization of byproducts, nontoxic and harmless brown granulated sugar has been used as a raw material for synthesizing CDs. Weak-blue-emitting CDs were prepared in one step by a hydrothermal method, and hydrothermal synthesis was used to extract red fluorescent carbon dots from chlorophyll to serve as a background reference (
                     Wang et al., 2018
                     ). The proposed methods offer the advantages of using abundant raw materials, simplicity, low/nontoxicity, and good stability and biocompatibility and are therefore environmentally friendly alternatives for material exploitation and application.


Scheme 1 shows the one-step solvothermal method used to synthesize both the BCDs with weak blue fluorescence and the RCDs with red fluorescence, which were subsequently used to construct a system for ratiometric fluorescence sensing. The as-prepared BCDs served as the functional response unit and initially exhibited almost imperceptible blue fluorescence. This result was obtained because the specific fluorescence properties of CDs heavily depend on the synthesis precursor and top-down synthetic strategies, as well as the interaction between individual particles (Li et al., 2021). Thus, the sensing system presents red fluorescence from RCDs in the absence of AMO. However, abundant hydroxyl and carboxyl groups, endow the as-prepared BCDs with good aqueous solubility (Qin et al., 2022, 2021; Hao et al., 2022; Zhang et al., 2022; Wang et al., 2022). Hydrophilic BCDs with multiple reaction sites are known to interact with target analytes via hydrogen bonds (Hua et al., 2018a). AMO is abundant in functional groups (C–O, C–N and COOH) and can successfully adsorb onto the outer surface of BCDs via the formation of strong hydrogen bonds. The attachment of functional groups to the BCD surface can promote the solubility of BCD to enable free dispersion in water. The AMO molecules adsorbed on the BCDs may alter the characteristic surface charge and effectively prevent contact of BCDs through electrostatic repulsion, thus reducing nonradiative decay and dramatically enhancing the fluorescence intensity (
Yang et al., 2014
). The formation of an AMO-BCDs conjugation system via hydrogen bonding also plays an important role in detection. The AMO-BCDs conjugation system may form via charge transfer facilitated by the electron accepting nature of the -COOH groups and the electron donating group of AMO (Hua et al., 2018b). The combined effect of hydrogen bonding and charge transfer can generate larger fluorophores (Serna-Galvis et al., 2017). The conjugates produce stronger emission than single BCDs under the same excitation. However, the RCDs serving as reference signals are insensitive to AMO because of the absence of specific conditions for forming hydrogen bonds. Therefore, the target AMO strongly interacts with the weakly emissive BCDs via hydrogen bonding to enhance the blue fluorescence, and the color change in the system fluorescence from red to blue enables the concentration-dependent visual detection of AMO. The high sensitivity and visual detection of the sensor to AMO can be attributed to this mechanism of enhanced emission induced by hydrogen bonding (Wu et al., 2022).
